  "prompt": "Why does Russia not join NATO?",
  "response": "Russia has not joined NATO for several key reasons:\n\n1. Historical and ideological differences\n- NATO was originally formed as a Western alliance against the Soviet Union during the Cold War\n- Russia viewed NATO as a potential military threat to its interests\n\n2. Conflicting geopolitical goals\n- NATO's eastward expansion into former Soviet bloc countries was seen by Russia as a threat\n- Russia wants to maintain its own sphere of influence in Eastern Europe and former Soviet states\n\n3. Different political and military philosophies\n- NATO is based on collective defense and democratic principles\n- Russia prefers to maintain independent military and strategic capabilities\n\n4. Mutual distrust\n- NATO countries have been critical of Russia's actions in places like Crimea and Ukraine\n- Russia has consistently opposed NATO's military interventions and expansion\n\n5. Strategic independence\n- Russia wants to maintain its status as a major global power without being constrained by NATO's collective decision-making\n\n6. Incompatible membership criteria\n- NATO requires members to meet certain democratic standards and resolve territorial disputes\n- Russia has not been willing to meet these conditions\n\nThe relationship between Russia and NATO has been consistently tense, with Russia viewing the alliance as a potential threat to its national security and strategic interests.",
